<br>
So...what do you think? What's your favorite part? Now is the time to interact with the book.<br>
<br>
Earlier today, I read a part that actually made me CRY. And I've read this book before! I love books that you can grow old with, that are always new and insightful. Sigh.<br>
<br>
Are there things in Little Women that apply to us today? Like what?<br>
<br>
<br>
And, hmm...next book...any suggestions? (On my shelf, I have some Tolstoy, some George Elliot, some Austen, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Tom Jones</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, Sharon Creech, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Treasure Island</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and some Dumas. And other stuff I can't see.) What sort of book goes well with April? <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:FF9900;font-family:Gigi;font-size:large;">Amy</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.nc.rr.com/peculiartreasure/images/bookline.gif "/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:99FF66;font-family:Enviro;font-size:x-small;">He who sedulously attends, pointedly asks, calmly speaks,<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> coolly answers, and ceases when he has no more to say, <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->is in possession of some of the best requisites of man.<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->     --Lavater</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bchristlikebooklovers.showUserPublicProfile?gid=femalenomad>FemaleNomad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezHopeful</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#3333ff>(3/27/03 7:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm22.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=30.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Classic Lit Book Club</span><hr size=1> FINISHED! <br>
<br>
So...any thoughts?<br>
<br>
I think I want to be like these little women. I want to cultivate the womanliness that each of the March girls showed: Meg's motherliness, Jo's determination to be wild in some way or other yet intensely loving and careful of &quot;her family,&quot; Beth's selflessness, and Amy's elegance and appreciation of the beautiful things. <br>
<br>
Do you think that's possible, anymore? I mean, I have a lot more to do than sit home and sew. Yet...I long for such a life! (If I could sew, that is!) <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:FF9900;font-family:Gigi;font-size:medium;">Amy</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.nc.rr.com/peculiartreasure/images/bookline.gif "/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-family:Enviro;font-size:x-small;">Act as though it were impossible to fail.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bchristlikebooklovers.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lilathlete>LiLaThLeTe</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.nc.rr.com/peculiartreasure/images/rainbow.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>EzCRAZY!</span><br>  Posts: 82<br> <font color=#3333ff>(3/28/03 12:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm22.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=30.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.myezboard.com/projects/ezboard/ezboard_userimages/godlovers80868/images/ACFtagdUQ.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Classic Lit Book Club</span><hr size=1> You know what I found when I read it.... I didn't really care for Mr. Bhaer.  Idk why.  Maybe b/c he was old(er) and I just couldn't be &quot;attracted&quot; to him like Jo.  Something just didn't work for me.... it was wierd <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:CC3399;font-family:comic sans ms;font-size:medium;"> <br>
